[
    {
        "content": "<p>If Dirac structures are analogous to symplectic structures, then what type of subspace of a Dirac manifold is analogous to a Lagrangian subspace?</p>",
        "id": 272739673,
        "sender_full_name": "Owen Lynch",
        "timestamp": 1645481491
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Maybe you mean \"what type of submanifold of a Dirac manifold is analogous to a Lagrangian submanifold of a presymplectic manifold?\"</p>",
        "id": 272872987,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1645567495
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Anyway, it sounds a bit tricky.   A submanifold <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">L</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span></span></span></span> of a presymplectic manifold <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> is <strong>isotropic</strong> iff for all points <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi>L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x \\in L</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.5782em;vertical-align:-0.0391em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∈</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span></span></span></span> and tangent vectors <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>v</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>w</mi><mo>∈</mo><msub><mi>T</mi><mi>x</mi></msub><mi>L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">v,w \\in T_x L</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7335em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">v</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02691em;\">w</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∈</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.1514em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.1389em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">x</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span></span></span></span> we have <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>ω</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>v</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>w</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\omega(v,w) = 0</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">ω</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">v</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02691em;\">w</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span></span></span></span>.  Then <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">L</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span></span></span></span> is Lagrangian iff it's a maximal isotropic submanifold.</p>",
        "id": 272873168,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1645567580
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In other words <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">L</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span></span></span></span> is isotropic iff the inclusion <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>i</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>L</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">i: L \\to X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6595em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">i</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> has <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>i</mi><mo>∗</mo></msup><mi>ω</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">i^\\ast \\omega = 0</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6887em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">i</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6887em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mbin mtight\">∗</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">ω</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span></span></span></span>.   Since 2-forms pull back, this is a natural condition.</p>",
        "id": 272873412,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1645567712
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But a Poisson manifold is defined using a bivector field <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Π</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Pi</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Π</span></span></span></span>, not a 2-form.</p>",
        "id": 272873449,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1645567733
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>And bivector fields push forward.  So for a Poisson manifold <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> it feels more natural to talk about quotient maps <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>p</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>X</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>M</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">p: X \\to M</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span></span></span></span> with <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>p</mi><mo>∗</mo></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Π</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">p_\\ast \\Pi = 0</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8778em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.1757em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mbin mtight\">∗</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord\">Π</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span></span></span></span></p>",
        "id": 272873605,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1645567815
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I don't know if people have studied these, but they should have!</p>",
        "id": 272873661,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1645567849
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Dirac manifolds are sort of a hybrid of these ideas, so it's even more confusing....</p>",
        "id": 272873679,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1645567863
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Maybe I can help a bit? What is the confusing part?</p>",
        "id": 272873870,
        "sender_full_name": "Markus Lohmayer",
        "timestamp": 1645567981
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Owen asked this question, more or less:</p>\n<p>Lagrangian submanifolds are to symplectic manifolds as <strong>what</strong> are to Dirac manifolds?</p>",
        "id": 272874439,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1645568324
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So any answer to that would be helpful.  I was just trying to explain why Lagrangian submanifolds are a very natural concept for presymplectic manifolds, but not so natural for Poisson manifolds.  Dirac manifolds generalize both presymplectic manifolds and Poisson manifolds.</p>",
        "id": 272874900,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1645568447
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>A Dirac structure is a Lagrangian submanifold, but it is not (co)isotripic wrt to some symplectic form, but rather with respect to some symmetric indefinite form. I guess you are aware of this. Therefore I am not so sure about the above question.</p>",
        "id": 272875077,
        "sender_full_name": "Markus Lohmayer",
        "timestamp": 1645568575
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Owen and I are thinking of Dirac manifolds (= manifolds with Dirac structure) as a simultaneous generalization of presymplectic and Poisson manifolds.   So, like presymplectic and Poisson manifolds, you can use them to describe \"phase spaces\" in physics.   From this viewpoint it makes sense to take as many concepts from symplectic geometry as one can, and generalize them to Dirac manifolds.   One of these is \"Lagrangian submanifold\".</p>\n<p>The fact that a Dirac structure has something (co)isotropic about its definition is not the main point here, I think.</p>",
        "id": 272875488,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1645568790
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It's possible that I'm quite confused.</p>",
        "id": 272875597,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1645568856
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Ah okay I see.</p>",
        "id": 272875602,
        "sender_full_name": "Markus Lohmayer",
        "timestamp": 1645568856
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So, do you know what a Lagrangian submanifold in symplectic geometry means in terms of a physical example?</p>",
        "id": 272875796,
        "sender_full_name": "Markus Lohmayer",
        "timestamp": 1645568964
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I don't. But I know why Dirac structures show up, and what (co)isotropy (wrt the indefinite form) means physically for them</p>",
        "id": 272875910,
        "sender_full_name": "Markus Lohmayer",
        "timestamp": 1645569010
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"318772\">Markus Lohmayer</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/306433-practice.3A-thermodynamics/topic/Lagrangian.20subspaces/near/272875796\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>So, do you know what a Lagrangian submanifold in symplectic geometry means in terms of a physical example?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Yes.   Most importantly for us perhaps, given symplectic manifolds <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span></span></span></span> thought of as phase spaces, a Lagrangian submanifold of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mover accent=\"true\"><mi>X</mi><mo stretchy=\"true\">‾</mo></mover><mo>×</mo><mi>Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\overline{X} \\times Y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.9667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord overline\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8833em;\"><span style=\"top:-3em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.8033em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"overline-line\" style=\"border-bottom-width:0.04em;\"></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span></span></span></span> describes a physically realistic relation between states of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> and states of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span></span></span></span>.    Here <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mover accent=\"true\"><mi>X</mi><mo stretchy=\"true\">‾</mo></mover></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\overline{X}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord overline\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8833em;\"><span style=\"top:-3em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.8033em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"overline-line\" style=\"border-bottom-width:0.04em;\"></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> is <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> with its symplectic structure multiplied by <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">-1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7278em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">−</span><span class=\"mord\">1</span></span></span></span>.</p>\n<p>For example <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> could be the space of position-momentum pairs of a particle at time 0, and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span></span></span></span> could be the space of position-momentum pairs of a particle at time 1.  Then time evolution via a Hamiltonian gives a relation between points in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> and points in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span></span></span></span>, and this relation is a Lagrangian submanifold <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi><mo>⊆</mo><mover accent=\"true\"><mi>X</mi><mo stretchy=\"true\">‾</mo></mover><mo>×</mo><mi>Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">L \\subseteq \\overline{X} \\times Y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8193em;vertical-align:-0.136em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⊆</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.9667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord overline\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8833em;\"><span style=\"top:-3em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.8033em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"overline-line\" style=\"border-bottom-width:0.04em;\"></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 272876771,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1645569505
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Another example is studied a lot in </p>\n<ul>\n<li>Baez and Fong, <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/1504.05625\">A compositional framework for passive linear networks</a>.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>where we show a large class of electrical circuits give rise to a Lagrangian relation between voltage-current pairs on the input wires and voltage-current pairs on the output wires.</p>",
        "id": 272876994,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1645569649
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(A <strong>Lagrangian relation</strong> between symplectic manifolds <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span></span></span></span> is a Lagrangian submanifold of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mover accent=\"true\"><mi>X</mi><mo stretchy=\"true\">‾</mo></mover><mo>×</mo><mi>Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\overline{X} \\times Y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.9667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord overline\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8833em;\"><span style=\"top:-3em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.8033em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"overline-line\" style=\"border-bottom-width:0.04em;\"></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span></span></span></span>.)</p>",
        "id": 272877051,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1645569689
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks John. I suppose I now understand your motivation. I recommend you the following article: <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/1804.04951.pdf\">https://arxiv.org/pdf/1804.04951.pdf</a> It explains the interconnection of port-Hamiltonian systems (i.e. the composition of power-preserving relations = Dirac structures) in terms of Dirac categories. You could like it ;)</p>",
        "id": 272877446,
        "sender_full_name": "Markus Lohmayer",
        "timestamp": 1645569923
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I got sleepy yesterday ;) So, I think the answer to \"Lagrangian submanifolds are to symplectic manifolds as what are to Dirac manifolds?\" is that Dirac manifolds are to Dirac manifolds what Lagrangian submanifolds are to symplectic manifolds, if that makes any sense :)</p>",
        "id": 272913239,
        "sender_full_name": "Markus Lohmayer",
        "timestamp": 1645601572
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I also want to mention that I like to think about Dirac structures as structures on vector bundles rather than on the base manifold. E.g. a Dirac structure on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"script\">X</mi><mo>⊕</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">F</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">T \\mathcal{X} \\oplus \\mathcal{F}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.14643em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">⊕</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.09931em;\">F</span></span></span></span>( where <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"script\">X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">T \\mathcal{X}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.14643em;\">X</span></span></span></span> is the tangent space of some manifold of system states <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{X}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.14643em;\">X</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">F</mi><mo>→</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{F} \\rightarrow \\mathcal{X}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.09931em;\">F</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.14643em;\">X</span></span></span></span> is some (usually trivial) vector bundle of port variables) is a vector subbundle of  <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"script\">X</mi><mo>⊕</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">F</mi><mo>⊕</mo><msup><mi>T</mi><mo>∗</mo></msup><mi mathvariant=\"script\">X</mi><mo>⊕</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"script\">F</mi><mo>∗</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">T \\mathcal{X} \\oplus \\mathcal{F} \\oplus T^* \\mathcal{X} \\oplus \\mathcal{F}^*</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.14643em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">⊕</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.09931em;\">F</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">⊕</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.772em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6887em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mbin mtight\">∗</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.14643em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">⊕</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6887em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.09931em;\">F</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6887em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mbin mtight\">∗</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> on which the canonical bilinear symmetric indefinite form vanishes (and hence I suppose it can be called a Lagrangian submanifold$ (wrt that form)).</p>",
        "id": 273251845,
        "sender_full_name": "Markus Lohmayer",
        "timestamp": 1645807279
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks!  Owen is starting to read your papers; maybe you two could talk about this stuff sometime.</p>",
